# Error Handling Standards

## Services Always Throw

Services must throw errors — never return them or swallow them silently:

```typescript
const result: ApiResponse<Feature[]> = await res.json();
if (!result.success) throw new Error(result.error ?? 'Failed to load features');
return result.data ?? [];
```

## HTTP Response Validation

Check `response.ok` before parsing for errors outside the `ApiResponse` envelope:

```typescript
const res = await fetch(url, options);
if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}: ${res.statusText}`);
const result: ApiResponse<T> = await res.json();
```

## React Query `onError` Handler

Handle errors in `useMutation`'s `onError` callback. Always narrow the error type before accessing `.message`.

```typescript
onError: (error) => {
  const message = error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Something went wrong';
  // Web:   toast.error(message)
  // Mobile: Alert.alert('Error', message)
},
```

## Never Silently Fail

❌ **BAD:**

```typescript
try {
  await featureService.delete(token, id);
} catch {
  // silently ignored — user has no idea what happened
}
```

✅ **GOOD — React Query's `onError` handles it automatically; no manual try/catch needed in components:**

```typescript
const { mutate: deleteFeature } = useMutation({
  mutationFn: async (id: string) => featureService.delete(token, id),
  onError: (error) => { /* show user feedback */ },
});
```

## Error Boundaries (Web)

Wrap feature pages in an error boundary to prevent full-app crashes on unexpected render errors. Use `react-error-boundary` with a fallback UI:

```typescript
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

<ErrorBoundary fallback={<div>Something went wrong. Please refresh.</div>}>
  <FeaturePage />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

## Error Shape

API errors always follow `ApiResponse<T>`:

```typescript
{ success: false, error: "Human-readable message" }
```

The `error` field value is shown directly to users. Keep messages clear and actionable.
